README.md
     1â†’# Archived project. No maintenance. 
     3â†’This project is not maintained anymore and is archived. Feel free to fork and
     4â†’make your own changes if needed. For more detail read my blog post: [Taking an indefinite sabbatical from my projects](https://arslan.io/2018/10/09/taking-an-indefinite-sabbatical-from-my-projects/)
     5â†’
     6â†’Thanks to everyone for their valuable feedback and contributions.
     7â†’
     8â†’# Structs
    10â†’Structs contains various utilities to work with Go (Golang) structs. It was
    11â†’initially used by me to convert a struct into a `map[string]interface{}`. With
    12â†’time I've added other utilities for structs.  It's basically a high level
    13â†’package based on primitives from the reflect package. Feel free to add new
    14â†’functions or improve the existing code.
    15â†’
    16â†’## Install
    18â†’```bash
    19â†’go get github.com/fatih/structs
    20â†’```
    21â†’
    22â†’## Usage and Examples
    24â†’Just like the standard lib `strings`, `bytes` and co packages, `structs` has
    25â†’many global functions to manipulate or organize your struct data. Lets define
    26â†’and declare a struct:
    27â†’
    28â†’```go
    29â†’type Server struct {
    30â†’	Name        string `json:"name,omitempty"`
    31â†’	ID          int
    32â†’	Enabled     bool
    33â†’	users       []string // not exported
    34â†’	http.Server          // embedded
    35â†’}
    36â†’
    37â†’server := &Server{
    38â†’	Name:    "gopher",
    39â†’	ID:      123456,
    40â†’	Enabled: true,
    41â†’}
    42â†’```
    43â†’
    44â†’```go
    45â†’// Convert a struct to a map[string]interface{}
    46â†’// => {"Name":"gopher", "ID":123456, "Enabled":true}
    47â†’m := structs.Map(server)
    48â†’
    49â†’// Convert the values of a struct to a []interface{}
    50â†’// => ["gopher", 123456, true]
    51â†’v := structs.Values(server)
    52â†’
    53â†’// Convert the names of a struct to a []string
    54â†’// (see "Names methods" for more info about fields)
    55â†’n := structs.Names(server)
    56â†’
    57â†’// Convert the values of a struct to a []*Field
    58â†’// (see "Field methods" for more info about fields)
    59â†’f := structs.Fields(server)
    60â†’
    61â†’// Return the struct name => "Server"
    62â†’n := structs.Name(server)
    63â†’
    64â†’// Check if any field of a struct is initialized or not.
    65â†’h := structs.HasZero(server)
    66â†’
    67â†’// Check if all fields of a struct is initialized or not.
    68â†’z := structs.IsZero(server)
    69â†’
    70â†’// Check if server is a struct or a pointer to struct
    71â†’i := structs.IsStruct(server)
    72â†’```
    73â†’
    74â†’### Struct methods
    76â†’The structs functions can be also used as independent methods by creating a new
    77â†’`*structs.Struct`. This is handy if you want to have more control over the
    78â†’structs (such as retrieving a single Field).
    79â†’
    80â†’```go
    81â†’// Create a new struct type:
    82â†’s := structs.New(server)
    83â†’
    84â†’m := s.Map()              // Get a map[string]interface{}
    85â†’v := s.Values()           // Get a []interface{}
    86â†’f := s.Fields()           // Get a []*Field
    87â†’n := s.Names()            // Get a []string
    88â†’f := s.Field(name)        // Get a *Field based on the given field name
    89â†’f, ok := s.FieldOk(name)  // Get a *Field based on the given field name
    90â†’n := s.Name()             // Get the struct name
    91â†’h := s.HasZero()          // Check if any field is uninitialized
    92â†’z := s.IsZero()           // Check if all fields are uninitialized
    93â†’```
    94â†’
    95â†’### Field methods
    97â†’We can easily examine a single Field for more detail. Below you can see how we
    98â†’get and interact with various field methods:
    99â†’
   100â†’
   101â†’```go
   102â†’s := structs.New(server)
   103â†’
   104â†’// Get the Field struct for the "Name" field
   105â†’name := s.Field("Name")
   106â†’
   107â†’// Get the underlying value,  value => "gopher"
   108â†’value := name.Value().(string)
   109â†’
   110â†’// Set the field's value
   111â†’name.Set("another gopher")
   112â†’
   113â†’// Get the field's kind, kind =>  "string"
   114â†’name.Kind()
   115â†’
   116â†’// Check if the field is exported or not
   117â†’if name.IsExported() {
   118â†’	fmt.Println("Name field is exported")
   119â†’}
   120â†’
   121â†’// Check if the value is a zero value, such as "" for string, 0 for int
   122â†’if !name.IsZero() {
   123â†’	fmt.Println("Name is initialized")
   124â†’}
   125â†’
   126â†’// Check if the field is an anonymous (embedded) field
   127â†’if !name.IsEmbedded() {
   128â†’	fmt.Println("Name is not an embedded field")
   129â†’}
   130â†’
   131â†’// Get the Field's tag value for tag name "json", tag value => "name,omitempty"
   132â†’tagValue := name.Tag("json")
   133â†’```
   134â†’
   135â†’Nested structs are supported too:
   136â†’
   137â†’```go
   138â†’addrField := s.Field("Server").Field("Addr")
   139â†’
   140â†’// Get the value for addr
   141â†’a := addrField.Value().(string)
   142â†’
   143â†’// Or get all fields
   144â†’httpServer := s.Field("Server").Fields()
   145â†’```
   146â†’
   147â†’We can also get a slice of Fields from the Struct type to iterate over all
   148â†’fields. This is handy if you wish to examine all fields:
   149â†’
   150â†’```go
   151â†’s := structs.New(server)
   152â†’
   153â†’for _, f := range s.Fields() {
   154â†’	fmt.Printf("field name: %+v\n", f.Name())
   155â†’
   156â†’	if f.IsExported() {
   157â†’		fmt.Printf("value   : %+v\n", f.Value())
   158â†’		fmt.Printf("is zero : %+v\n", f.IsZero())
   159â†’	}
   160â†’}
   161â†’```
   162â†’
